history.content: Probably not. Make the proper back up arrangements. To get into the class you would have to talk to the CS department, not the professor. Very unlikely the CS department would enroll you into the class just because you were "close" on the wait list.

children.subject: And according to the advisor I’ve already spoken to, cs 189 is definitely important for the career I’m looking into.

I doubt any sort of appeal would actually cause a change but you should probably still try?

My question is what kind of career are you looking into that requires exactly 189? If you want to do applied ML taking other courses as well as having personal projects will help you way more than taking 189. If you really require the theoretical knowledge from 189, you could just read through the lecture notes online on your own time and you'd get a pretty good grasp of the material. If you need to have the words "Machine Learning" on your transcript there are plenty of other alternatives to 189
I’m sure every student on the waitlist could give and argument on why they deserve to be on the class over others. You can’t talk you want in, you just have to hope the waitlist clears.

It’s not just because I’d be close on the waitlist. I have many reasons for taking this class and I can outline them, specifying my future career goals and the specific topics and prerequisites I need to master in order to get there.
Lots of people drop 189, so sit there and hang tight. Hopefully it works out, but I can't really see a feasible appeal process where you get in ahead of people above you on the waitlist

history.content: I am currently in waitlist ~195 (not a CS major) and I really really hope that I could take this class because I plan to use ML a lot for my career. I tried to phase 1 this class but at that time, it was already full so I had to wait until they expanded the waitlist so my number is pretty low... If I somehow don't get in, is it possible to talk to the professor if I end up getting pretty close on the waitlist? I'd be sad if I can't take it :(
history.subject: If I stuck through CS 189, will I have a chance to get in?
